ln 1517, one John Heynes, a vintner and baker‚ who had some years before been discommoned for selling bad wine and bread‚ collected a band of dis- affected Benedictines and Cistercians‚ and about the silent time of night, issuing forth at Carfax upon the proctor and his retinue, encountered them manfully. The outcries and clashing of arms caused the bur- ghers to come from their beds with lights, and the battle was stayed. The monks were arrested and Heynes banished.

In 1518 the University surrendered its privileges into the hands of Cardinal Wolsey, and during the years next following several unimportant skirmishes took place between the Town and the charterless University, in one of which the scholars of Broadgates Hall, led on by Thomas Wynkynstay and armed with bows arrows and swords fell upon the King's watch- men and slew one, Hugh Todd.
